1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+ {
This cunning move seeks to disorganize Black's forces, taking advantage of the
threatening power of White's central pawns. This line, known as the Taimanov
Attack, became popular in the 50's of the last century and has been considered
a real threat to the Modern Benoni ever since. In this sense is very
symptomatic what Lev Psakhis revealed in the introduction to his book "The
Complete Benoni" Bastford 1995, "Recently White has favoured Taimanov's plan
of 7 f4 and 8. Bb5+ against which I had not had the youthful enthusiasm to
defend for some five years. These days I only play the Benoni after 1. d4 Nf6
2 c4 e6 3. Nf3 and now 3 ... c5, which cuts out this and other worrying plans.
"  In spite of Psakhis’ opinion, there are several Modern Benoni players who
are ready to take the challenge and defend its beloved defence.  The present
work explains the details needed to make them regret this decision.} Bd7 $2 {
[#] This line is very dubious and can't be recommended for Black. Even though
being acquainted with the concrete details of the forthcoming complications is
very important for White's players.} 9. e5 $1 {The key to punishing Black´s
risky play lies in this energetic central advance. The logic behind this
decision is simple since d7 is occupied, Black’s knight on f6 doesn’t have
good squares.  Now let’s analyse Black’s possible reactions A) 9...Nh5, B)
9...Qe7 and C) 9...dxe5.} dxe5 {[#]} (9... Qe7 {[#] Although this move hides
some ideas that could be poisonous for White, the reality is that it does not
solve Black’s problems.} 10. Qe2 ({The natural} 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Ne8 $1 {
would give Black a playable position.}) 10... dxe5 11. d6 $1 Qd8 ({Black’s
queen is misplaced and is not surprising that the choice was of no help either:
} 11... Qe6 12. Bc4 Qg4 (12... Qf5 13. fxe5 Ng4 14. Nd5 Nc6 15. h3 Ngxe5 16. g4
$18) 13. fxe5 O-O ({The transition to an endgame does not reduce White’s
pressure,} 13... Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Ng4 15. Nd5 O-O 16. e6 $1 Bxe6 17. Nc7 Nc6 18.
Nxe6 fxe6 19. Bxg4 $18) 14. Nf3 Nc6 15. exf6 $1 Rae8 16. fxg7 Rxe2+ 17. Bxe2
Kxg7 18. O-O {with decisive material advantage.}) 12. fxe5 O-O 13. Nf3 Nc6 {
Other continuations do not improve the Black situation either.} (13... Bxb5 14.
Nxb5 Nd5 15. O-O $16) (13... Ng4 14. Bg5 Qb6 15. O-O-O Re8 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17.
Nd5 Qa5 18. Kb1 $16) 14. Bg5 Re8 ({Black finds no relief on,} 14... h6 15. Bxf6
Bxf6 16. exf6 Re8 17. Ne4 Rxe4 18. Qxe4 Qa5+ 19. Kf2 Qxb5 20. Qe2 $16) 15. O-O
h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qf2 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Rad1 {White’s powerful
passed pawn gives him an indisputable advantage.}) (9... Nh5 {Bringing the
knight to h5, changing in e5 or maintaining the tension, is simply favourable
for white.} 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Bxd7 Qxd7 (11... Nxd7 {It wouldn’t have helped
Black’s interests.} 12. g4 $1 Nxf4 13. Bxf4 dxe5 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bh4 Qb6 16.
Qb3 {with a very advantageous ending for White.}) 12. O-O Na6 {[#]} 13. Ne4 $1
{Faced with a very poor coordination of the enemy’s pieces, white does its
best to open lines.} dxe5 14. fxe5 Rae8 15. Re1 $1 {After this move, White is
one step away from consolidating his powerful pawn center; the poor situation
of the Black knights is striking.} Kh8 ({It is not possible to capture the
central pawn} 15... Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 17. Nf6+ Nxf6 18. Rxe5 {White’s
material advantage is close to being decisive.}) 16. Bg5 {White’s advantage
led the game Marques, V - Del Bosco, R Sao Paulo 1997 to a beautiful
conclusion:} Bxe5 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. Qxh5 $1 f5 ({Capturing the queen also did
not improve the Black possibilities} 18... gxh5 19. Bf6+ Kg8 20. Bxe5 f5 21.
Nf6+ Rxf6 22. Bxf6) 19. Nf6 Rfe8 20. Rxe5 {With decisive advantage.}) 10. fxe5
Nh5 ({White gets a comfortable advantage after} 10... Qe7 11. Nf3 O-O 12. Bg5
h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. O-O Bxe5 (14... Bg7 15. Re1 $16) 15. Re1 f6 16. d6 Qe6 17.
Qd3 Kg7 18. Bc4 Qf5 19. Nxe5 fxe5 20. Ne4 Bc6 21. Bd5 $16) 11. Nf3 O-O (11...
Bxb5 12. Nxb5 O-O 13. O-O c4 14. Nc3 {White’s advantage is indisputable.})
12. Bxd7 Nxd7 ({Trying to preserve the material equilibrium by} 12... Qxd7 {
does not solve Black’s problems either; White’s strong central pawns added
to the hopeless situation of the Black’s knight on h5, gives White a clear
edge.} 13. O-O Na6 14. Qa4 $1 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 {[%csl Gh5]} Bh8 16. g4 Ng7 17. Bg5
{with a crushing advantage.}) 13. g4 $1 Bxe5 ({The complications starting after
} 13... Nxe5 {are interesting, but as usual, favourable for White.} 14. gxh5
Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Qh4+ 16. Kf1 Rae8 17. Kg2 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Re5 19. Rf1 Rf5 20. Qe2
Rxh5 21. Bf4 Rxd5 22. Rae1 {Although Black has managed to collect three pawns
in return for the sacrificed piece, White enjoys a considerable advantage as
his extra bishop will soon tell.}) 14. gxh5 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Re8+ 16. Kf2 Nf6 17.
Rf1 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Bd2 {Although the position is clearly
favourable for White, Black has some drawing chances.} *

