1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+
Nbd7 $6 {[#] In the 90s this line was considered risky for Black, but from the
first years of the 21st century, when 17.Bf1 was discovered, it became clear
that it is almost unplayable for Black. The general theme of the lines that
arise after 8...Nbd7 can be summarized like this: White tries to consolidate
and use his material advantage; on the other hand, Black tries to achieve some
sort of counterplay.} 9. e5 $1 dxe5 {The alternatives lead to greater material
losses and, in addition, neither improve Black’s possibilities:} (9... Nh5 $2
10. e6 Qh4+ 11. Kf1 Ng3+ 12. hxg3 Qxh1 13. Qa4 O-O 14. exd7 {In the game
Thompson,B (1949)-Weiss,L (1866) Internet 2005 White’s material advantage
proved decisive.}) (9... Qe7 $2 10. Qe2 $18) (9... O-O $2 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Nf3
a6 12. Be2 b5 13. O-O Re8 {In the game Nesterov, A - Cohen Revivo, S
Montevideo 2017, White could have consolidated his material advantage with the
simple} 14. a3 Bd7 (14... Bb7 15. f5 $1) 15. h3) 10. fxe5 Nh5 11. e6 {[#]} Qh4+
({Black didn’t get enough compensation for the lost material after} 11... O-O
$2 12. exd7 Bxd7 (12... Qh4+ 13. Kf1 Ng3+ 14. hxg3 Qxh1 15. Qg4 $5 a6 16.
dxc8=Q Raxc8 17. Bd7 Rcd8 18. Bg5 {White’s material advantage was decisive
in the game Neurohr, S-Link, M St Ingbert 1993.}) 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Nge2 Qf5 (
14... b5 15. O-O b4 16. Ne4 $18) {This position was seen in the game Van Seben,
E -Van Scheepen, F IECG email 2002, at this point White could have
consolidated his material advantage by playing the precise,} 15. Rf1 $1 $146
Qd7 ({The active} 15... Qg4 {is answered with a timely artificial castling} 16.
Kf2 $1 Rfe8 17. Kg1 {White’s advantage is decisive.}) 16. Qa4 $1 Qe7 17. Bd2
b5 {A desperate attempt.} 18. Nxb5 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Rfe8 20. Qc4 {Leads nowhere as
there is no trace of Black’s compensation.}) ({The forced sequence that
emerges after} 11... fxe6 12. dxe6 O-O 13. exd7 Qh4+ 14. g3 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Qe4+
16. Qe2 Qxh1 17. Be3 Bxd7 18. Bxd7 {leaves White with a winning advantage as
happened in the game Ilic, D -Ruisinger, W Chiasso 1991.}) (11... Bxc3+ 12.
bxc3 Qh4+ 13. g3 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Qxh1 15. Be3 {Transposes to the main line.}) 12.
g3 Nxg3 ({Changing the of move order only provides extra options for White.} 
12... Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Nxg3 (13... Qe4+ 14. Qe2 Qxh1 15. exd7+ Kd8 16. Qe8+ {
winning.}) 14. hxg3 {Transposes to the main line 12...Ng3.} Qxh1 15. exd7+ $5
Bxd7 16. Qe2+ Kf8 17. Bxd7 Qxg1+ 18. Kd2 Qxg3 19. c4 {White’s powerful
bishop pair gives him a winning position.}) 13. hxg3 Qxh1 ({The sacrifice} 
13... Qxg3+ $2 {easies White’s task} 14. Kd2 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Qg2+ 16. Ne2
Qxd5+ 17. Kc2 {in the game Mertens-De Smet, K Belgium 1986 White’s advantage
transformed itself quickly into a victory.}) 14. Be3 $1 {[#] Now Black has the
following options A)14...a6; B)14...00; C)14...Qg2 and D)14...Bc3.} Bxc3+ (
14... Qg2 {[#]} 15. exd7+ Bxd7 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17. Qa4+ ({White’s most
accurate continuation is} 17. Qg4+ {transposing to the position that emerges
on move 19 of this variation.}) 17... Kd8 18. Qh4+ Kd7 19. Qg4+ f5 20. Qa4+ Kc8
21. O-O-O Bxc3 22. bxc3 Qxg3 ({The transition to an endgame offered a more
stubborn resistance, even so, White’s advantage would remain decisive as can
