holdable for Black} Qxf3 17. Nxf3 (17. exd7+ Bxd7 18. Bxd7+ Kxd7 19. Nxf3 Rae8
20. Kd2 b6) 17... fxe6 18. dxe6 a6 $1 19. exd7+ Bxd7 20. Bxd7+ Kxd7 21. O-O-O+
Kc7 22. Bxc5 {As in the game Fleischmann,S-Beyer,U Germany 1991.}) (16. exd7+
$1 Bxd7 17. Qd3) {Let's continue with the analysis of 16.Qd3!} 16... Qxd3 17.
exd7+ Bxd7 18. Bxd3 {[#]} b6 19. Bg5 f6 (19... O-O 20. Bf6 Rfe8+ 21. Kf2 b5 22.
Nf3 {White’s pieces are on its way to destroying Black’s position as
happened in the game Sage, F (2321) -Simeonov, L (2150) ICCF email 2011.}) 20.
Bxf6 O-O 21. Be7 Rfe8 (21... Rf7 22. d6 $18) 22. d6 {The rest was a matter of
