1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+
Nfd7 9. Bd3 $1 {I've preferred this move to the more popular 9.a4 with the
intention of avoiding the following line} (9. a4 O-O 10. Nf3 Na6 11. O-O Nb4 {
Which is considered to be very playable for Black.} ({After} 11... Nc7 12. Bd3
{the game would transpose to chapter 7 of our proposed repertoire.})) 9... Qh4+
10. g3 Qe7 {Black provokes g3 to slightly weaken White’s kingside, thus
improving the options of which is, usually, the problem piece in the modern
Benoni, the light squared bishop. Of course, Black must pay a price for this
